messages.message:
Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/ext/spl/spl_observer.c\n+++ b/ext/spl/spl_observer.c\n@@ -746,8 +746,13 @@\n     if ((element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &intern->pos)) == NULL) {\n         RETURN_NULL();\n     }\n-    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);\n-    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);\n+    zval tmp;\n+    ZVAL_COPY_VALUE(&tmp, &element->inf);\n+    ZVAL_UNDEF(&element->inf);\n+    zval_ptr_dtor(&tmp);\n+    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);\n }\n'}`
responded: The use-after-free is likely caused by the following sequence in `zim_SplObjectStorage_setInfo` (ext/spl/spl_observer.c):

```c
749|     zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);
750|     ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);
```

If `element->inf` is a reference-counted zval (e.g., object, string, array), `zval_ptr_dtor` will free the memory if the refcount drops to zero. However, if the memory for `element` itself is freed as a side effect (e.g., if the storage is rehashed or the element is deleted in a destructor), then the next line `ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);` will access freed memory, causing a use-after-free.

**The correct fix** is to make a temporary copy of `element->inf`, call `zval_ptr_dtor` on the temporary, and only proceed to write to `element->inf` if `element` is still valid. However, since we cannot easily check if `element` is still valid after `zval_ptr_dtor`, the safest approach is to use `ZVAL_COPY_VALUE` to a temporary, set `element->inf` to `UNDEF` before calling `zval_ptr_dtor`, then assign the new value.

This pattern is used elsewhere in PHP core to avoid UAF in similar situations.

**Proposed patch:**
```diff
--- a/ext/spl/spl_observer.c
+++ b/ext/spl/spl_observer.c
@@ -749,8 +749,13 @@
     if ((element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &intern->pos)) == NULL) {
         RETURN_NULL();
     }
-    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);
-    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);
+    zval tmp;
+    ZVAL_COPY_VALUE(&tmp, &element->inf);
+    ZVAL_UNDEF(&element->inf);
+    zval_ptr_dtor(&tmp);
+    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);
 }
```

