messages.message:
Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/ext/spl/spl_observer.c\n+++ b/ext/spl/spl_observer.c\n@@ -746,8 +746,19 @@\n     if ((element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &intern->pos)) == NULL) {\n         RETURN_NULL();\n     }\n-    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);\n-    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);\n+    HashPosition pos = intern->pos;\n+    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);\n+    /* After dtor, element may have been deleted, so re-fetch */\n+    element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &pos);\n+    if (element) {\n+        ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);\n+    }\n }\n'}`
responded: The sanitizer report and the code show that the use-after-free occurs because the element pointed to by `element` can be freed as a side effect of `zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);` (for example, if the destructor for the object stored in `inf` removes the element from the storage, or if `removeAll` is called recursively).

**The only safe way** is to get the hash position before the destructor call, and after the destructor, re-fetch the element pointer from the hash table using the saved position. If the element is gone, we must not write to it.

Here is a robust fix:

```diff
--- a/ext/spl/spl_observer.c
+++ b/ext/spl/spl_observer.c
@@ -746,8 +746,19 @@
     if ((element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &intern->pos)) == NULL) {
         RETURN_NULL();
     }
-    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);
-    ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);
+    HashPosition pos = intern->pos;
+    zval_ptr_dtor(&element->inf);
+    // After dtor, element may have been deleted, so re-fetch
+    element = zend_hash_get_current_data_ptr_ex(&intern->storage, &pos);
+    if (element) {
+        ZVAL_COPY(&element->inf, inf);
+    }
 }
```

This ensures we never write to a freed element.

Let's validate this patch.

